column27: Something I would do differently is scheduling our team meetings more formally. For this project, we had team meetings weekly at first, but towards the end of the semester we began to have them biweekly or on different days/times. This was harder to keep up with because the only reminder was our groupchat. Instead, it would have been helpful for one of us to have created a google calendar invite with a date, time, and place for our meeting. This would ensure we were all aware of the meeting.
column28: This form of organization was very effective for our team because we all had different roles at different points of our project, therefore ensuring everyone was able to access any changes or updates made was essential. For instance, at the beginning I designed and laser cut our soundproof box. By adding the design files into our shared folder, I ensured that everyone had access to the final design, dimensions, etc which was later helpful to our teammates who were writing our final report. This made our project development smoother because it avoided confusion.
column29: A formal scheduling method would impact a team meetings effectiveness because it would ensure clarity - everyone knows where and when the meeting is happening - whereas a simple text in a groupchat might not be seen by everyone, it would effectively remind the teammates of the meeting,  given that calendar invites usually have an alert minutes before the meeting, and it would formally establish the event.

column28:
We were very ambitious with our goals from the start of the semester. Instead of sticking to only one method we decided to go with two methods: tensile testing and 3 point bending. Because of this our testing time doubled, as the number of test runs that we did was equal for both method, coming in at 60 trials for each one. 
This allowed us to see the differences between the two methods and see if any correlation existed between the two types. Obviously a lot of quality work was done here, which allowed us to have a good analysis within our experiment.
column29:
We were very ambitious with our goals from the start of the semester. Instead of sticking to only one method we decided to go with two methods: tensile testing and 3 point bending. Because of this our testing time doubled, as the number of test runs that we did was equal for both method, coming in at 60 trials for each one. 
The large number of trials is good for experiments, but we probably could have done an even better experiment if we focused on one method of testing and increased the number of trials by a bit. I started to realized how ambitious we set our goals to be when I started to see other groups finish their experiment when we were only half way done with ours. 
For future teams, I would dedicate more time in the initial part to set up a general timeline so that we can determine how much time we should be spending on experiments while still having adequate time to perform the analysis.

The regular updates took place during our weekly team meetings, where each member shared their progress on assigned tasks and flagged any issues they encountered. For example, one challenge we faced was a delay in collecting certain data due to equipment availability. By discussing it early, we were able to reallocate tasks and adjust our timeline to stay on track.

The positive outcomes of this consistent communication included improved alignment within the team, faster problem-solving, and a greater sense of accountability. It ensured that everyone was aware of the projectâ€™s status and allowed us to adapt quickly to any changes or obstacles.
column29:
In one situation, two team members had their tasks mixed up, but no one brought it up until much closer to the deadline. This mix-up led to confusion about who was responsible for what and caused delays in completing those tasks, requiring the team to rush to make adjustments and finish on time.

To prevent this in the future, I would propose implementing a task review system early in the process, where the team double-checks and confirms their responsibilities at the start of the project and during regular updates. I would also encourage an open forum during meetings where members can clarify roles and ask questions if anything seems unclear.

By addressing such issues earlier, the team would benefit from better organization, reduced stress, and a stronger ability to deliver quality results on time.

column27: Although our communication was very good, the way that we divided up work was not the greatest. There was never a clear, concrete method of deciding who was doing what parts when it came to an assignment. For example, in almost all of the milestones, we would talk about when it is due and what we had to do to complete it and then we would just start working. People would start in different places and eventually we would all meet in the middle and finish it up. Because of this, some people end up doing more than others and, overall, the way work is divided could be much more effective and it will definitely be something I think about in future teams.
column28: One specific situation where communication and being accessible helped us all was when we didn't really have an idea as to where our project was heading in the beginning. Our group had not set a date and time to discuss this topic and we had gone a few days without speaking. Out of the blue, David messaged our group chat and mentioned that we should probably start thinking about the next steps moving forward. The rest of the team, including me, immediately replied and we even started talking about it right then and there. The ability to be so accessible allowed our team to solve issues as soon as possible, even immediately sometimes. To make sure that our team felt supported, I would always ask others if they needed help or I would always be willing to help if somebody else asked me for it. Even if it wasn't necessarily something that was my part, I would still try my best to be useful. Effective communication definitely played a part in my team's success because it allowed us to be more at ease knowing that our teammates were just a message away, no matter the date or time. This gave us a sense of comfort working with each other because we knew that we were always there to support and help each other.

Next time, I will be sure to assign or ask my teammates to assign themselves sections of the reports so that we know which parts to do and which parts not to touch and leave to the others. Implementing these changes would be a good impact because then everyone would know what they are doing and how much of it they are doing.
